default&#xa0;default3. Response to Questions default3.default1default Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?default3.
default2
default A number of policy measures have been introduced to incentivise energy efficiency improvements to reduce the 
defaultdemand for heat. These include the Green Deal and ECO with minimum energy performance an entry requirement for the domestic RHI.
default3.
default3
default 
defaultIt should be noted that there is a limit to which heat demand can be reduced through energy efficiency in much of the UK’s 
defaultbuilding stock. Many older properties would require substantial and un-economic (even with Green Deal Finance) improvements to make a meaningful reduction in heat demand. In other circumstances, such as with listed buildings and in natural conservation are
defaultas, many demand reducing measures will be unsuitable.
default3.
default4
default 
defaultIt therefore makes sense to target low carbon and renewable heating solutions at those buildings which are using the most harmful fuels (off the gas grid) and 
defaultfor which it will be 
defaulthardest to reduce 
defaultdemand. The associated ‘’bang for buck’’ in applying a renewable system in such circumstances will be much higher compared to a building where demand can be substantially reduced through efficiency and where the primary heating fuel is gas.
