default defaultBiomass heating is one of the most efficient methods of producing renewable energy. There are substantial opportunities to improve the way biomass defaultis utilised in heating within the UKdefault, through more efficient heating systems, cost reduction in manufacture and installation, alternative feedstocks and process innovations such as torrefaction. 
default3.11 
defaultTorrefaction
default is the thermochemical treatment of biomass
default at 200 to 320C, carried out under atmospheric pressure and in the absence of oxygen. Torrefied pellets can be produced from a wide range of biomass feedstocks and 
defaultt
defaulthe process removes 
defaultwater and other substances leaving
default a solid material which can be densifi
defaulted into briquettes or pellets. 
defaultThe main advantage of this process is that each torrefied pellet could contain twice the energy as those pellets available today; this reduces transportation and storage costs. 
defaultThe 
defaultimplementation of the RHI presents a medium 
defaultterm commercial opportunity for existing technologies and users. However, the Heat Strategy illustrates that 
defaultmore support for the biomass industry is required to ensure it can fulfil its important role defaultin developing new innovative technologiesdefault.default3.1
